57. Inane et ventis animam committe] As to ‘I nunc' see x. 310, n. ‘Dolato ligno' is not a smooth plauk as Mr. Mayor says, but rough—hewn with a dolabra. (S. viii. 248.) A ‘digitus' was one-sixteenth of an English foot: four or seven is a conventional way of speaking. See xiv. 289. Heinrich refers to the say- ing ascribed to Anacharsis by Diogenes Laertius (i. 103), μαθὼν τέτταρας δακτύ- λους εἶναι τὸ πάχος τῆς νέως, τοσοῦτον, ἔφη, τοῦ θανάτου τοὺς πλέοντας ἀπέχειν. Ruperti has abundance of quotations on the terrors of the deep, which Horace sums up in xvoful ternis in the third ode of the first book. ‘Taeda' is the generic name for the trees yielding tar, including several varieties of the ‘pi11us,’ of which many were used 111 ship-build- ing: for which reason ‘pinus' is fre- quently used for a ship, though ‘taeda’ only here.
